A diverse array of ideologies, fashion, and other forms of expression, visual art, dance, literature and film largely characterized by anti-establishment views and the promotion of individual freedom, centred on a loud, aggressive genre of rock music called punk rock.

A cultural and social movement that began in the mid-1980s as an offshoot of the punk subculture. It is distinguished by its discontent with society in general, and specifically society's disapproval of the LGBTQ community. Queercore expresses itself in a D.I.Y. style through magazines, music, writing and film.
Any of various subcultures within the LGBTQ community.

An underground LGBTQ subculture that originated in the United States, in which people "walk" (i.e., compete) for trophies, prizes, and glory at events known as balls. Ball participants are mainly young Black and Latina members of the LGBTQ community. Attendees can spectate, dance, vogue, and/or walk in one or more of the numerous drag categories that are designed to emulate other genders and social classes, while offering a sort of escape from reality. This culture extends beyond the extravagant events as most participants in ball culture belong to groups known as "houses" that mimic a family structure and offer similar support.
